<property name="hibernate.javax.cache.uri">ehcache.xml</property>
actually mean?

It tells Hibernate where to find the JCache provider‚Äôs configuration file.

Longer, correct explanation

Hibernate itself does NOT understand Ehcache XML.

Instead:

    Hibernate talks to JCache (JSR-107)
    JCache talks to Ehcache
    Ehcache reads ehcache.xml


This property is the bridge that says:

‚ÄúHey Hibernate, when you initialize JCache, pass this URI to the cache provider.‚Äù
<property name="hibernate.javax.cache.uri">ehcache.xml</property>

Means:

    -Load ehcache.xml
    -From the classpath
    -Typically located in src/main/resources/ehcache.xml


Internally

Hibernate does something like:
    CachingProvider provider = Caching.getCachingProvider();
    URI uri = URI.create("ehcache.xml");
    CacheManager cacheManager = provider.getCacheManager(uri, classLoader);


    So:
    ‚ùå Hibernate doesn‚Äôt parse the XML
    ‚úÖ Ehcache does


Why does the property still say javax in Jakarta?
hibernate.javax.cache.*

Why this is still correct in Hibernate 6
    JCache spec name is still javax.cache
    Jakarta did NOT rename JCache
    Only JPA / JAXB / Transactions moved to jakarta.*


